04791nam a22007815i 9780231520416DE-B159720220302035458.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220302t20102010nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a2009025569  a(OCoLC)979953830  a97802315204167 a10.7312/vatt148282doi  a(DE-B1597)459406  a(OCoLC)690877334  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY00aBR100b.V3513 2010 7aREL0510002bisacsh04a261.2/12221 aVattimo, Gianni, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aChristianity, Truth, and Weakening Faith :bA Dialogue /cGianni Vattimo, René Girard; ed. by Pierpaolo Antonello. 1aNew York, NY : bColumbia University Press, c[2010] 4c©2010  a1 online resource (136 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tCONTENTS -- tNOTE ON THE TEXT -- tINTRODUCTION -- t1. CHRISTIANITY AND MODERNITY -- t2. FAITH AND RELATIVISM -- t3. HERMENEUTICS, AUTHORITY, TRADITION -- t4. HEIDEGGER AND GIRARD -- t5. NOT JUST INTERPRETATIONS, THERE ARE FACTS, TOO -- tNOTES -- tBIBLIOGRAPHY0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe debate over the place of religion in secular, democratic societies dominates philosophical and intellectual discourse. These arguments often polarize around simplistic reductions, making efforts at reconciliation impossible. Yet more rational stances do exist, positions that broker a peace between relativism and religion in people's public, private, and ethical lives.Christianity, Truth, and Weakening Faith advances just such a dialogue, featuring the collaboration of two major philosophers known for their progressive approach to this issue. Seeking unity over difference, Gianni Vattimo and René Girard turn to Max Weber, Eric Auerbach, and Marcel Gauchet, among others, in their exploration of truth and liberty, relativism and faith, and the tensions of a world filled with new forms of religiously inspired violence. Vattimo and Girard ultimately conclude that secularism and the involvement (or lack thereof) of religion in governance are, in essence, produced by Christianity. In other words, Christianity is "the religion of the exit from religion," and democracy, civil rights, the free market, and individual freedoms are all facilitated by Christian culture. Through an exchange that is both intimate and enlightening, Vattimo and Girard share their unparalleled insight into the relationships among religion, modernity, and the role of Christianity, especially as it exists in our multicultural world.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mrz 2022) 0aChristianity and culture. 0aChristianityxPhilosophy. 0aRelativity. 7aRELIGION / Philosophy.2bisacsh1 aAntonello, Pierpaolo, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAntonello, Pierpaolo, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aG, René, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGirard, René, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut1 aGirard, René, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMcCuaig, William.1 aVattimo, Gianni, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertColumbia University Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013z978311044247240uhttps://doi.org/10.7312/vatt1482840uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780231520416423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780231520416/original  a978-3-11-044247-2  Columbia University Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  